{"cursor":"9795","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Latent heat' is the heat released or absorbed by a body or a thermodynamic\nsystem during a process that occurs without a change in temperature. A typical\nexample is a change of state of matter, meaning a phase transition such as the\nmelting of ice or the boiling of water. {{cite book\n|author=Perrot, Pierre |title=A to Z of Thermodynamics |publisher=Oxford\nUniversity Press |year=1998 |isbn=0-19-856552-6 }} {{cite book\n|author=Clark, John, O.E. |title=The Essential Dictionary of Science\n|publisher=Barnes & Noble Books |year=2004 |isbn=0-7607-4616-8 }} The term\nwas introduced around 1762 by Joseph Black. It is derived from the Latin latere\n(to lie hidden). Black used the term in the context of calorimetry when\nreferring to the heat transferred that caused a change of volume while the\nthermodynamic system was held at constant temperature.\n\nIn contrast to latent heat, an energy is called a sensible energy or heat, when\nit causes processes that do result in a change of the temperature of the system.\n","linknr":426,"url":"Specific_latent_heat","recorded":1362375095,"links":46,"instances":["physics","matter","physics","mass"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Thermochemistry","Atmospheric thermodynamics","Thermodynamics"],"headings":["Usage","History","Specific latent heat","Table of latent heats","Latent heat for condensation of water","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Carnot_heat_engine_2.svg/220px-Carnot_heat_engine_2.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/4/354c808b3ac7ff5bd75faa26bcc36220.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/9/e/b9ece18c950afbfa6b0fdbfa4ff731d3.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/e/7/de71b72c4f62f20d117414dd2f33ca25.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/d/9/8d9c307cb7f3c4a32822a51922d1ceaa.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/f/7/af7e8a85df47250ffab736b7a8807488.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/a/e/2aede3b55c027fe4392429d6474